t.Request(endpoint, data=data, headers=headers)).read().decode())\"\n```\n\nHowever, we need to be careful with quoting. The outer double quotes will be interpreted by the shell; we can avoid complex quoting by using single quotes around the entire python3 -c argument, and using double quotes inside for dict keys etc. In Python single quotes are fine. So we can do:\n\n```\npython3 -c 'import os, json, urllib.request; key=os.getenv(\"MATON_API_KEY\"); print(\"Key present:\", bool(key)); endpoint=\"https://gateway.maton.ai/google-mail/v1/send\"; payload=json.dumps({\"from\":\"OpenCopilot Digest <austin.king@parallon.com>\",\"to\":\"austin.king@parallon.com\",\"subject\":\"MATON test\",\"text\":\"Hello – quick test\"}); data=payload.encode(); headers={\"Authorization\":f\"Bearer {key}\", \"Content-Type\":\"application/json\"}; print(\"Status:\", urllib.request.urlopen(urllib.request.Request(endpoint, data=data, headers=headers)).getcode()); print(\"JSON reply:\", urllib.request.urlopen(urllib.request.Request(endpoint, data=data, headers=headers)).read().decode())'\n```\n\nBut inside single quotes, we need to escape any single quotes that appear inside the Python code. There are none, except the f-string uses single quotes around 'Bearer {key}'. Actually we use double quotes for the f-string: f\"Bearer {key}\" maybe easier. Let's rewrite using double quotes for the outermost Python string and single quotes inside? Actually the outermost is single quotes for the whole command; inside we can use double quotes for strings without escaping. That's easier: we can wrap the entire Python snippet in single quotes, and inside use double quotes for strings. That is safe as long as we don't have unescaped single quotes inside.\n\nSo:\n\n```\npython3 -c 'import os, json, urllib.request; key = os.getenv(\"MATON_API_KEY\"); print(\"Key present:\", bool(key)); endpoint = \"https://gateway.maton.ai/google-mail/v1/send\"; payload = json.dumps({\"from\":\"OpenCopilot Digest <austin.king@