if it's not set, we can advise the user. But the user specifically wants us to run the minimal test. Maybe we should attempt to run a simpler command that just prints the environment variable to see if it's set.\n\nLet's try something simpler first: `echo $MATON_API_KEY`. That will just output the value or nothing. Then we can perhaps run the Python snippet only if it's set. But we can just run the snippet regardless; if the key is missing, the script will note that.\n\nThus, we can run the Python snippet directly; it will check `os.getenv(\"MATON_API_KEY\")` and print whether it's present.\n\nThus, we can exec:\n\n```\npython3 -c 'import os, json, urllib.request; key = os.getenv(\"MATON_API_KEY\"); print(\"MATON_API_KEY present:\", bool(key)); print(\"Key value length:\", len(key) if key else 0); endpoint = \"https://gateway.maton.ai/google-mail/v1/send\"; payload = json.dumps({\"from\":\"OpenCopilot Digest <austin.king@parallon.com>\",\"to\":\"austin.king@parallon.com\",\"subject\":\"MATON test\",\"text\":\"Hello – quick test\"}); data = payload.encode(); headers = {\"Authorization\": f\"Bearer {key}\", \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\"} ; print(\"Sending request...\"); try: response = urllib.request.urlopen(urllib.request.Request(endpoint, data=data, headers=headers)); print(\"Status:\", response.getcode()); print(\"Reply:\", response.read().decode()); except Exception as e: print(\"Error:\", e); print(\"Raw error:\", e.read() if hasattr(e, \"read\") else str(e))'\n```\n\nBut again quoting issues.\n\nAlternatively, we can exec a shell command that runs a small Python script from a file maybe easier? But we don't have a file.\n\nAnother approach: Use `python3 - <<'PY' ... PY` to feed multi-line script. That may be simpler to embed because we can use single quotes around the delimiter.\n\nExample:\n\n```\nbash -c 'python3 - <<\\\"PY\\\"\\nimport os, json, urllib.request\\nkey = os.getenv(\"MATON_API_KEY\")\\nprint(\"Key present:\", bool(key))\\npayload = {\\n 